Brexit, and what then?
NEW YORK – It will take a lot of time for Britain, Europe and the world to digest the implications of the "Brexit" referendum carried out by the United Kingdom.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people initially thought the EU would not "cut off the branch it was sitting on": after all, a amicable divorce appears to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – might become complicated.
The economic and commercial integration benefits between the UK and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU were to take its conviction that more economic integration is desirable seriously, its leaders would seek to ensure that the links remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Or, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes for companies in Luxembourg and now president of the European Commission, seems to take a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that in order to dissuade other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no concessions, giving the UK barely more than what the World Trade Organisation agreements guarantee it.
In other words, Europe must not be kept united by the benefits it offers to its members, which greatly exceed its costs.
Economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and the pride of being a European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, Europe must be maintained by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position doesn't take into account a lesson that is clear, however, both in the vote in favour of Brexit and in the Republican Party primaries in the United States: a significant part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades has perhaps been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
The time has now come.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider that trade agreements are the source of their misfortunes.
Although it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's commercial agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
Not unexpectedly, the results were one-way: workers' negotiating position has weakened further, thus exacerbating the effects of the legislations that diminish the unions' weight and employees' rights.
Although commercial agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance towards capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have given pharmaceutical companies greater power to increase prices.
In other words, any increase in market power of firms de facto implies a reduction in real wages – an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
Industrial concentration is rising in many sectors - and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have been added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services on which many low- and middle-income workers depend.
The economic uncertainty that results for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of the wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for everyone, but especially for former colonial powers.
However, despite many probably denying it, an increase in unskilled labor supply leads – as long as we are in the presence of normal negatively sloped demand curves – to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment increases.
This is most worrying in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high overall level of unemployment.
Europe, particularly the euro zone, has been very poorly managed over the past decades, to the point where its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unimpeded migration in Europe means that countries that have been more successful in reducing unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
Workers in these countries support the cost of lower wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a cheaper workforce.
The burden of refugees, as no surprise, is borne by those who are least able to do so.
Yes, there are a lot of discussions about the net benefits of immigration.
In a country offering a low level of guaranteed services – social protection, education, healthcare, etc. – to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and compressions in public services has been the evisceration of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households did not benefit from the economic growth.
They understand that the banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions allocated for saving the banks, and insignificant amounts for saving their homes and jobs.
While the real median income (adjusted for inflation) for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, voter anger should not surprise anyone.
In addition, politicians who promised change failed to meet expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unjust, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing what little trust they still had in the ability or will of traditional politicians to correct it.
This too is understandable: new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for all.
However, an angry vote does not solve the problems, and may instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
It's the same if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment has been able to do so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider the improvement of ordinary citizens' well-being as its main objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing goals and means: for instance, free trade, if well managed, could bring a greater shared prosperity; but if it's badly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living for many - perhaps most - citizens.
There are alternatives to current neoliberal measures that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives – such as the transatlantic trade and investment partnership proposed by U.S. President Barack Obama – that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the first and avoid the second.
